      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument for segregation at the time often centered on the idea of maintaining cultural homogeneity and social order. Proponents claimed that separating groups preserved distinct cultural identities, allowing communities to develop according to their own traditions without outside interference. Furthermore, some argued that controlled separation was necessary to prevent social friction and maintain perceived stability within established social hierarchies.",
